{"title_page": "98th Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 98th Regiment Illinois Volunteer Infantry/Illinois Volunteer Mounted Infantry\n| image=Flag of Illinois.svg\n| image_size = 100\n|caption=Illinois flag\n|dates= September 3, 1862, to July 29, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Mounted infantry]]\n|equipment= [[Spencer repeating rifle]]\n| battles = [[American Civil War]]\n* [[Battle of Hoover's Gap]]\n* [[Battle of Chickamauga]]\n* [[Battle of Resaca]]\n* [[Siege of Atlanta]]\n}}\nThe '''98th Regiment Illinois Volunteer Infantry''', later the '''98th Regiment Illinois Volunteer Mounted Infantry''', was an [[infantry]] and [[mounted infantry]] [[regiment]] that served in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]]<ref name=\"Dyer\">Dyer</ref>.\n\n==Service==\nThe 98th Illinois Infantry was organized at [[Centralia, Illinois]] and mustered into Federal service on September 3, 1862<ref name=\"OoB\">Official Records of the American Civil War of the Union and Confederate Armies, U.S. War Department</ref><ref>Baumgartner, p. 70</ref><ref name=\"Reece\">Reece</ref>.\n\nThe regiment was converted to mounted infantry on March 8, 1863<ref name=\"Repeaters\">Wilder's Lightning Brigade and Its Spencer Repeaters, Sunderland</ref>\n. An element of \"Wilder's [[Lightning Brigade (US Army of the Cumberland 1863)|Lightning Brigade]]\", a unit that pioneered the use of [[mounted infantry]].<ref name=\"Lightning\">Lightning at Hoover's Gap: the Story of Wilder's Brigade, Sunderland</ref> As part of that brigade, it performed admirably in the Tullahoma<ref name=\"Rob1\">The Fall of Chattanooga, Robertson</ref><ref name=\"Lightning\" /><ref name=\"Kennedy225\">Kennedy, p. 225.</ref> and Chickamauga campaigns. Its superior firepower<ref name=\"Repeaters\">Wilder's Lightning Brigade and Its Spencer Repeaters, Sunderland</ref> due to its Spencers was found to allow it to take on an enemy that outnumbered them on several occasions and triumph. Also, the rapidity of movement afforded by their mounts gave them a rapid response ability that could take and maintain the initiative from the rebels<ref name=\"Rob2\">McLemore's Cove, Robertson</ref> This combat power prevented much larger Confederate units from crossing a bridge on the first day of Chickamauga<ref name=\"Rob3\">The Armies Collide, Robertson</ref><ref name=\"Rob4\">Day 1, Robertson</ref> and stopped the left column of the Bragg's key breakthrough on the second day<ref name=\"Rob5\">Day 2, Robertson</ref>.\n\nThe regiment was mustered out on June 27, 1865, and discharged at [[Springfield, Illinois]], on July 7, 1865<ref name=\"OoB\">Official Records of the American Civil War of the Union and Confederate Armies, U.S. War Department</ref>.\n\n==Total strength and casualties==\nThe regiment suffered 30 enlisted men who were killed in action or who died of their wounds and 5 officers and 136 enlisted men who died of disease, for a total of 171 fatalities.<ref name=\"Dyer\" />\n\n==Commanders==\n*Colonel John J. Funkhouser - Discharged due to wounds July 5, 1864.<ref>http://www.rootsweb.com/~ilcivilw/f&s/098-fs.htm Illinois in the Cvil war website after Illinois Adjutant General's muster rolls</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n{{reflist}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/blue-lightning-wilders-mounted-infantry-brigade-in-the-battle-of-chickamauga/oclc/232639520?loc=02333\n| title       = Blue Lightning: Wilder's Mounted Brigade in the Battle of Chickamauga\n| author      = Baumgartner, Richard A.\n| publisher   = Blue Acorn Press\n| location    = Huntington WV\n| year        = 2007\n| isbn        = 978-1-885033-35-2\n| asin        = \n| oclc        = \n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/three-years-in-the-army-of-the-cumberland-the-letters-and-diary-of-major-james-a-connolly/oclc/906602437&referer=brief_results\n| title       = Three Years in the Army of the Cumberland: The Letters and Diary of Major James A. Connolly\n| author      = Connolly, James A.\n| editor      = Paul M. Angle\n| publisher   = Indiana University Press\n| location    = Bloomington, IN\n| year        = 1959\n| isbn        = 9780527190002\n| asin        = \n| oclc        = 906602437\n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.battlefields.org/learn/primary-sources/battle-hoovers-gap\n| title       = Primary Sources: The Road to Chickamauga\n| author      = Connolly, James A\n| publisher   = American Battlefield Trust\n| location    = Washington, DC\n| year        = \n| isbn        = \n| asin        = \n| oclc        = \n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/autumn-of-glory-the-army-of-tennessee-1862-1865/oclc/1147753151?referer=di&ht=edition\n| title       = Autumn of Glory: The Army of Tennessee 1862\u20131865\n| author      = Connelly, Thomas L\n| publisher   = Louisiana State University Press\n| location    = Baton Rouge, LA\n| year        = 1971\n| isbn        = 0-8071-2738-8\n| asin        = \n| oclc        = 1147753151\n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/this-terrible-sound-the-battle-of-chickamauga/oclc/53818141&referer=brief_results\n| title       = This Terrible Sound: The Battle of Chickamauga\n| author      = Cozzens, Peter\n| publisher   = University of Illinois Press\n| location    = Champaign, IL\n| year        = 1992\n| isbn        = 9780252065941\n| asin        = \n| oclc        = 53818141\n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/edge-of-glory-a-biography-of-general-william-s-rosecrans-usa/oclc/906813341&referer=brief_results\n| title       = The Edge of Glory: A Biography of General William S. Rosecrans, U.S.A.\n| author      = Daniel, Larry J. and Lamers, William M.\n| publisher   = Harcourt, Brace & World\n| location    = New York, NY\n| year        = 1961\n| isbn        = 9780807123966\n| asin        = \n| oclc        = 906813341\n| url-access  = \n}}*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://archive.org/details/35812648.3150.emory.edu/page/n9/mode/2up\n| title       = Morgan's Cavalry\n| author      = Duke, Basil W.\n| publisher   = Neale Pub. Co.\n| location    = New York, NY\n| year        = 1906\n| isbn        = \n| asin        = \n| oclc        = 35812648\n| url-access  = \n}}{{PD-notice}}\n*{{cite book\n| url         = https://archive.org/details/08697590.3359.emory.edu\n| title       = A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion\n| author      = Dyer, Frederick H. \n| publisher   = Dyer Pub. Co.\n| location    = Des Moines, IA\n| year        = 1908\n| isbn        = \n| asin        = B01BUFJ76Q\n}}{{PD-notice}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/longest-night-a-military-history-of-the-civil-war/oclc/892938160&referer=brief_results\n| title       = The Longest Night: A Military History of the Civil War\n| author      = Eicher, David J.; McPherson, James Alan \n| publisher   = Simon & Schuster\n| location    = New York, NY\n| year        = 2001\n| isbn        = 9780743218467\n| asin        = \n| oclc        = 892938160\n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://archive.is/20120829203141/http://www.dean.usma.edu/history/web03/atlases/american_civil_war/\n| title       = West Point Atlas of American Wars\n| author      = Esposito, Vincent J.\n| publisher   = Frederick A. Praeger\n| location    = New York, NY\n| year        = 1959\n| isbn        = \n| asin        = \n| oclc        = 5890637\n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/encyclopedia-of-the-american-civil-war-a-political-social-and-military-history/oclc/317783094&referer=brief_results\n| title       = Encyclopedia of the American Civil War: A Political, Social, and 